english:
  title: A Eulogy for the Painted Shakyamuni Buddha
  author: Kang Seok-deok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Son of the Wheel-Turning King, yet like an orphan or a widower cast adrift.
    In hemp robes on a grass mat, his wild hair matted, his face worn thin—
    even before he drew first breath, he had already redeemed the world's suffering.
    Why then choose such torment? Why sit in the perilous mountains,
    knees bent in emptiness?
    Hark!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Wheel-Turning King' (금륜왕) refers to Shuddhodana, the wealthy king and father of Prince Siddhartha, who would become the Buddha. The poem emphasizes the stark contrast between his royal birth and his later ascetic renunciation.
  - key: ''
    value: The speaker questions the necessity of the Buddha's self-imposed hardships, given that his compassion and enlightenment were already complete from birth. This reflects a tension in Buddhist philosophy between the doctrine of innate Buddha-nature and the necessity of spiritual practice.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Hark!'' (咄) is an exclamatory interjection often used in Zen Buddhist discourse to startle listeners into awakening.'
